\textbf{Vertical Asymptotes}

We know that vertical asymptotes occur when the denominator is zero.
Here our denominator is

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}x^2-3
\end{align*}

which is zero if $\scriptstyle x=\pm\sqrt{3}$. Therefore we have
vertical asymptotes at $\scriptstyle x=-\sqrt{3}$ and
$\scriptstyle x=\sqrt{3}$.

To see how the function looks near the asymptotes we could take some
limits. However, from
{part
(d)} we have that the function is decreasing to the left of
$\scriptstyle x=-\sqrt{3}$ as well as to the right. Therefore we
conclude that

\begin{align*}
\lim_{x\to-\sqrt{3}^-}f(x)=-\infty
\end{align*}

while

\begin{align*}
\lim_{x\to-\sqrt{3}^+}f(x)=+\infty
\end{align*}

We have the exact same conclusion about the other vertical asymptote at
$\scriptstyle x=\sqrt{3}$ since it has the same decreasing properties as
$\scriptstyle x=\sqrt{3}$.

\textbf{Horizontal or Slant Asymptotes}

We check for horizontal or slant asymptotes. Since the degree of the
numerator is larger than the degree of the denominator then we do not
have any horizontal asymptotes. However, the degree of the numerator is
exactly one larger than the degree of the denominator and so we do
expect slant asymptotes. To figure out the slant asymptote we perform
polynomial long division

\begin{align*}
\begin{array}{cccccccccccc}
&&&&&x&+&1&&&&\\
&&&&&\_&\_&\_&\_&\_&\_&\_\\
x^2&+&0x&-&3)&x^3&+&x^2&-&2x&-&3\\
&&&&&x^3&+&0x^2&-&3x&&\\
&&&&&\_&\_&\_&\_&\_&\_&\_\\
&&&&&&&x^2&+&x&-&3\\
&&&&&&&x^2&+&0x&-&3\\
&&&&&\_&\_&\_&\_&\_&\_&\_\\
&&&&&&&&&x&&
\end{array}
\end{align*}

Therefore we write $\displaystyle {}x^3+x^2-2x-3=(x^2-3)(x+1)+x$. So we
get that

\begin{align*}
\frac{x^3+x^2-2x-3}{x^2-3} &= \frac{(x^2-3)(x+1)+x}{x^2-3} \\
&= x+1+\frac{x}{x^2-3}
\end{align*}

Notice that for the last term,

\begin{align*}
\lim_{x\to\infty}\frac{x}{x^2-3}=0.
\end{align*}

Therefore as \emph{x} gets big we see that

\begin{align*}
\frac{x^3+x^2-2x-3}{x^2-3}
\end{align*}

looks like \emph{x+1}. If we take \emph{x} going to
$\scriptstyle -\infty$ we see that the limit of the last term still
vanishes and it still looks like $x+1$. Therefore, we conclude that
$x+1$ is a slant asymptote to the function.

\textbf{Summary}

Finally then we conclude that the equations for the vertical asymptotes
are

\begin{align*}
x&=-\sqrt{3}\\
x&=\sqrt{3}
\end{align*}

while the equation of the slant asymptote is

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}y=x+1.
\end{align*}

statement_latex:
Consider the function

\begin{align*}
f(x) = \frac{x^3+x^2-2x-3}{x^2-3}
\end{align*}

Its first and second derivatives are given by

\begin{align*}
f'(x) = \frac{(x^2-1)(x^2-6)}{(x^2-3)^2}
\end{align*} and

\begin{align*}
f''(x) = \frac{2x(x^2+9)}{(x^2-3)^3}
\end{align*}

Find any asymptotes of the function f(x) and write their equations.
